471
00:33:46,457 --> 00:33:50,200
And there were a lot of interesting feedback from the streamers.

472
00:33:50,200 --> 00:33:54,023
So sometimes we would actually acknowledge the feedback and act on it

473
00:33:54,023 --> 00:33:58,607
and give credit to the streamer or player after implementing that change.

474
00:34:00,910 --> 00:34:03,330
And then, you know, in a couple of days,

475
00:34:03,330 --> 00:34:05,291
it will be our one year anniversary.

476
00:34:05,291 --> 00:34:08,231
And so we, you know, launched our early access

477
00:34:08,231 --> 00:34:09,411
on March 23rd.

478
00:34:09,411 --> 00:34:13,452
And in 16 days, something happened.

479
00:34:13,452 --> 00:34:16,393
Like we were, we got like the Guinness record

480
00:34:16,393 --> 00:34:20,414
for selling 1 million units on Steam as an early access game

481
00:34:20,414 --> 00:34:22,094
and then we got six other records

482
00:34:22,094 --> 00:34:26,055
for selling too many copies in a very short time,

483
00:34:26,055 --> 00:34:27,495
which was unexpected.

484
00:34:29,283 --> 00:34:32,485
No one expected this in our team.

485
00:34:32,485 --> 00:34:35,388
Brandon and I were the most optimistic people.

486
00:34:35,388 --> 00:34:37,129
We were cheerleaders and our devs were like,

487
00:34:37,129 --> 00:34:41,273
you guys are crazy, you guys just watch Twitch too much,

488
00:34:41,273 --> 00:34:43,495
you guys hear good things from the streamers,

489
00:34:43,495 --> 00:34:45,917
you guys are too optimistic, you gotta calm down.

490
00:34:45,917 --> 00:34:47,739
But Brandon and I would be like,

491
00:34:47,739 --> 00:34:49,140
we're gonna sell two million copies,

492
00:34:49,140 --> 00:34:50,801
and they're like, you guys are being ridiculous.

493
00:34:51,282 --> 00:34:54,848
But, you know, we hit the record and it's all history.

494
00:34:54,848 --> 00:34:57,954
And then during early access, we launched our PUBG Partner Program.

495
00:34:57,954 --> 00:34:59,456
And the PUBG Partner Program is...

496
00:35:04,910 --> 00:35:10,852
something we were able to launch during early access because we became a bit successful during early access.

497
00:35:10,852 --> 00:35:16,774
We are now in a position where we were able to reward streamers for streaming our game.

498
00:35:16,774 --> 00:35:24,417
So we had a sign up page on our website where streamers would come and enter their information

499
00:35:24,417 --> 00:35:26,958
and we would select streamers that had...

500
00:35:27,718 --> 00:35:31,379
that could be a great part of our community,

501
00:35:31,379 --> 00:35:33,580
and we would give them rewards.

502
00:35:33,580 --> 00:35:37,602
Rewards like VIP access to our parties

503
00:35:37,602 --> 00:35:39,562
and access to custom games.

504
00:35:39,562 --> 00:35:41,563
Custom games is a feature in our game

505
00:35:41,563 --> 00:35:44,004
where you can create custom games for your community

506
00:35:44,004 --> 00:35:47,825
and then change the settings of Val Royale in our game.

507
00:35:47,825 --> 00:35:52,227
And then there were other perks that comes with the program.

508
00:35:54,422 --> 00:36:03,808
So the key points of early access, we continued to give benefits, but now we had the resources

509
00:36:03,808 --> 00:36:09,292
and some money to give back. And we wanted to give them bigger exposure.

510
00:36:10,173 --> 00:36:18,777
We launched a small advertising campaign and we were able to feature a lot of streamers there.

511
00:36:18,777 --> 00:36:25,780
So we had a Facebook and YouTube campaign where we would grab clips of Twitch streamers enjoying the game.

512
00:36:26,301 --> 00:36:31,586
it's available on our YouTube channel and you can see, you know, we tried to capture all the crazy

513
00:36:31,586 --> 00:36:36,872
moments they had and it's so fun to watch because their reactions were crazy. This was a new game to

514
00:36:36,872 --> 00:36:43,198
them and there were a lot of, you know, funny bugs and glitches and we just showed it all so that

515
00:36:43,198 --> 00:36:47,963
people would think, oh, like, I want to play that game. What kind of, you know, game is that we...

516
00:36:48,644 --> 00:36:52,027
had that ad campaign and it gives them exposure.

517
00:36:52,027 --> 00:36:56,091
And all the streamers that participated in this

518
00:36:56,091 --> 00:36:58,352
just did it for free.

519
00:36:58,352 --> 00:37:01,055
And we later rewarded them.

520
00:37:01,055 --> 00:37:04,598
So we also did the in-game graffiti event

521
00:37:04,598 --> 00:37:06,139
that I showed you earlier

522
00:37:06,139 --> 00:37:08,881
and it gave them access to custom games.

523
00:37:08,881 --> 00:37:09,362
And...

524
00:37:10,137 --> 00:37:17,784
The other thing we did was we created events to really celebrate the community that we built with them.

525
00:37:17,784 --> 00:37:22,508
And one of the most successful events we ever did was the Twitch Charity Invitational.

526
00:37:23,283 --> 00:37:28,369
You can find out more about the event if you Google it, but basically it was...

527
00:37:28,369 --> 00:37:32,915
We invited 64 streamers from North America and another 64 from Europe.

528
00:37:32,915 --> 00:37:42,547
And we had this huge group of streamers fighting with each other throughout a few games.

529
00:37:43,508 --> 00:37:49,434
we got so much exposure through this and the viewers loved it because they always love when

530
00:37:49,434 --> 00:37:57,922
there's rivalry going on among Twitch streamers and we were able to hit an all-time peak in terms

531
00:37:57,922 --> 00:37:58,782
of viewership.

532
00:37:59,685 --> 00:38:03,447
And we also had a streamer exclusive Pax East Mixer

533
00:38:03,447 --> 00:38:06,949
where we would invite content creators and Twitch streamers

534
00:38:06,949 --> 00:38:09,931
and really, you know, communicate with them.

535
00:38:09,931 --> 00:38:11,752
We had, you know, Brandon come in

536
00:38:11,752 --> 00:38:15,214
and he would talk about what's in store for PUBG,

537
00:38:15,214 --> 00:38:17,676
how we plan to continue to develop the game

538
00:38:17,676 --> 00:38:18,736
until we launch 1.0.

539
00:38:21,900 --> 00:38:24,788
There were other programs and activities we did.

540
00:38:24,788 --> 00:38:27,014
We had Dev Livestreams.

541
00:38:27,014 --> 00:38:28,798
You can watch that on our official Twitch channel.

542
00:38:31,451 --> 00:38:35,074
Yeah, we had, we, you know, arranged it ourselves.

543
00:38:35,074 --> 00:38:37,517
There were a lot of audio and sound issues.

544
00:38:37,517 --> 00:38:40,780
You should definitely watch it to learn what not to do in your dev livestreams

545
00:38:40,780 --> 00:38:45,884
because there are so many issues and it shows how we are not prepared,

546
00:38:45,884 --> 00:38:51,009
but kind of not afraid to give it a go and fail fast and learn quickly.

547
00:38:51,009 --> 00:38:52,550
But you should definitely watch if you plan

548
00:38:52,550 --> 00:38:54,853
to do like a dev livestream for the first time.

549
00:38:55,433 --> 00:39:02,859
And we gave rewards to all the alpha testers, which was the player unknown set, which is not available anymore.

550
00:39:02,859 --> 00:39:12,046
And we attended Twitch meetups. Twitch is a bit interesting because they have a lot of local meetups in different cities and states.

551
00:39:12,046 --> 00:39:17,310
And we attended those meetups to talk to streamers and talk about our game.

552
00:39:17,310 --> 00:39:20,593
So I was like a salesperson for our game.

553
00:39:21,294 --> 00:39:26,693
any months and you have to understand what it's like to be a streamer so

554
00:39:27,972 --> 00:39:33,296
I created my own Twitch channel and streamed for three months.

555
00:39:33,296 --> 00:39:37,239
And I highly encourage that to all the community managers

556
00:39:37,239 --> 00:39:42,163
who do not stream because it really helps you understand

557
00:39:42,163 --> 00:39:47,967
what it feels like to get donations and grow your following.

558
00:39:47,967 --> 00:39:52,411
And that really helped me understand how they think

559
00:39:52,411 --> 00:39:55,433
when they want to grow their business and to viewers.

560
00:39:56,656 --> 00:40:00,158
And it's also important to what it's like to be a viewer or a fan.

561
00:40:00,158 --> 00:40:05,882
So what I did was I watched Twitch like all day long

562
00:40:05,882 --> 00:40:10,725
during our alpha or beta phase and wanted to understand what kind

563
00:40:10,725 --> 00:40:13,727
of relationship they build with their viewers.

564
00:40:13,727 --> 00:40:18,770
At one point I was subscribed to 50 streamers and I was just paying that out

565
00:40:18,770 --> 00:40:21,732
of my own pocket. I just wanted to support them for being

566
00:40:21,732 --> 00:40:24,594
such a passionate part of our community.

567
00:40:24,594 --> 00:40:25,894
But it really helps like.

568
00:40:26,375 --> 00:40:32,659
because they know that you are from a small team and I'm just, you know, like a fangirl that want to support them

569
00:40:32,659 --> 00:40:35,500
and it also helped me build like a special relationship.

570
00:40:37,995 --> 00:40:41,097
So just to go over the key points,

571
00:40:41,097 --> 00:40:46,080
these are the points that I wanted to really highlight

572
00:40:46,080 --> 00:40:47,661
through today's talk.

573
00:40:47,661 --> 00:40:51,183
Number one, you have to start with a small,

574
00:40:51,183 --> 00:40:55,225
like exclusive community of hand-selected members first.

575
00:40:55,225 --> 00:40:59,088
We had the privilege of starting with a small community

576
00:40:59,088 --> 00:41:02,370
that Brandon already had built for many, many years,

577
00:41:02,370 --> 00:41:05,231
and they were already big fans of Balrial Games.

578
00:41:05,772 --> 00:41:10,592
And what's important is that to really strengthen that sense of exclusivity.

579
00:41:10,592 --> 00:41:14,373
If it's open to anyone, they're not going to be really interested.

580
00:41:14,373 --> 00:41:19,394
They want to be treated special, and they want to have something

581
00:41:19,394 --> 00:41:23,155
that's just exclusive to a small group of people.

582
00:41:23,155 --> 00:41:29,556
And if you take good care of them and start treating them differently

583
00:41:29,556 --> 00:41:35,137
after a certain time, they just become like genuine ambassadors for your gang.

584
00:41:37,025 --> 00:41:42,149
The second point would be that you have to, you know, especially for streamers,

585
00:41:42,149 --> 00:41:47,152
you have to give them something exclusive, something they can consume.

586
00:41:47,152 --> 00:41:51,255
Even if it's just a small nugget of information that's really important to

587
00:41:51,255 --> 00:41:55,278
their business and you have to make them feel like an insider.

588
00:41:55,278 --> 00:41:56,579
And that really.

589
00:41:57,420 --> 00:42:05,244
helps them build their business and for testers, they feel like they belong to the community.

590
00:42:05,244 --> 00:42:11,708
And you know, you allow them to shape your game by allowing them to give feedback and you act

591
00:42:11,708 --> 00:42:18,332
on them and you have to communicate the changes you made based on their feedback. And it's also

592
00:42:18,332 --> 00:42:25,096
important to communicate how, what they will gain from being part of this community. It's

593
00:42:26,733 --> 00:42:30,475
they're in it for some reason, they want something back.

594
00:42:30,475 --> 00:42:32,716
It's not that you have to pay them

595
00:42:32,716 --> 00:42:36,297
or have to reward them in some way,

596
00:42:36,297 --> 00:42:38,358
but it's always good to provide them

597
00:42:38,358 --> 00:42:41,300
with all the perks or benefits you can.

598
00:42:41,300 --> 00:42:44,481
And while it's difficult to do that as a small team

599
00:42:44,481 --> 00:42:46,562
without a big budget,

600
00:42:46,562 --> 00:42:48,883
there are a lot of things that you could try.

601
00:42:48,883 --> 00:42:52,225
I've shared the examples, and if you go to our dev blog,

602
00:42:52,225 --> 00:42:54,366
you will find a lot of evidence there.

603
00:42:55,876 --> 00:43:00,838
The things that we could have done but didn't do because we didn't have time,

604
00:43:00,838 --> 00:43:04,979
I still kind of feel like if we gave in-game badges for Alpha testers,

605
00:43:04,979 --> 00:43:07,981
that would be really cool because you can brag about that.

606
00:43:07,981 --> 00:43:12,782
And we wanted to launch an activity point program to reword testers

607
00:43:12,782 --> 00:43:16,584
that were more active than the rest of the community,

608
00:43:16,584 --> 00:43:18,125
but we didn't have time to.

609
00:43:18,125 --> 00:43:19,705
So it's something that you could look into.

610
00:43:20,446 --> 00:43:27,772
And, you know, it also, we wanted to have like a multi-tiered reward program for the streamers and testers.

611
00:43:27,772 --> 00:43:32,577
But we're just busy, I was busy handing out keys and talking to all our testers.

612
00:43:32,577 --> 00:43:38,763
So this is something you could, I would like to do if I could turn back time.

613
00:43:40,156 --> 00:43:44,038
The third point, content creators, Twitch streamers,

614
00:43:44,038 --> 00:43:47,500
they have to be part of your marketing plan

615
00:43:47,500 --> 00:43:48,860
if you don't have the budget,

616
00:43:48,860 --> 00:43:51,622
and they will help you if you build

617
00:43:51,622 --> 00:43:53,563
the relationship the right way.

618
00:43:53,563 --> 00:43:55,224
But they're not marketing tools.

619
00:43:56,084 --> 00:43:59,428
A lot of publishers pay them to play the game.

620
00:43:59,428 --> 00:44:02,131
You're not going to be able to build a relationship by doing that.

621
00:44:02,131 --> 00:44:03,592
And it's just a one-off thing.

622
00:44:03,592 --> 00:44:06,796
Like, they have to be emotionally invested.

623
00:44:06,796 --> 00:44:10,459
And to do that, you have to commit to building

624
00:44:10,459 --> 00:44:13,522
a mutually beneficial relationship with them.

625
00:44:13,522 --> 00:44:15,865
You have to, you know, invest a lot of your time.

626
00:44:15,865 --> 00:44:17,206
That's how I did it.

627
00:44:17,935 --> 00:44:21,580
And to do that, you know, you have to understand their business.

628
00:44:21,580 --> 00:44:27,347
You have to, you know, you highly recommend streaming yourself

629
00:44:27,347 --> 00:44:33,175
and becoming their hardcore fans and also treat them as your business partners.

630
00:44:35,428 --> 00:44:42,131
The last point I wanted to emphasize was that you have to directly talk to your players and streamers.

631
00:44:42,131 --> 00:44:49,835
Having an agency or outside help is always good when you only have limited time,

632
00:44:49,835 --> 00:44:53,677
but you should only do that when you want to scale things up,

633
00:44:53,677 --> 00:45:02,221
or when you don't really have the time to reach out to someone who's not a hardcore fan or who is like a...

634
00:45:04,202 --> 00:45:11,768
streamer that wants to support you, but not as someone, you know, as passionate as your key, like, tester.

635
00:45:11,768 --> 00:45:19,154
Because you have to directly talk to them to build relationships, and that level of intimacy you build

636
00:45:19,154 --> 00:45:22,316
like, grows and then helps you in the end.

637
00:45:24,373 --> 00:45:30,235
If I could turn back time, I would rethink how I want to build a team out.

638
00:45:30,235 --> 00:45:36,217
Because when we came out of early access, we didn't anticipate the kind of success we had.

639
00:45:36,217 --> 00:45:40,479
And we only had a few people in the community.

640
00:45:40,479 --> 00:45:43,300
I was the one who started talking to the streamers.

641
00:45:43,960 --> 00:45:50,664
and there were community coordinators and assistant community managers that would interact with the testers.

642
00:45:50,664 --> 00:46:00,751
And I really regret not scaling fast enough to be able to communicate to a community that would grow exponentially in the next few months.

643
00:46:00,751 --> 00:46:06,635
And we also failed to maintain the level of transparency we had in 2016 and 2017,

644
00:46:06,635 --> 00:46:12,439
because things grew so fast and we were not ready for that.

645
00:46:13,059 --> 00:46:20,314
So I highly recommend growing the team before things take off so you're ready for that kind

646
00:46:20,314 --> 00:46:23,561
of exposure and the need for interaction.

647
00:46:25,850 --> 00:46:31,012
So that's it for my talk and thanks for your time.

648
00:46:31,012 --> 00:46:34,574
And we're currently growing our team based in Amsterdam,

649
00:46:34,574 --> 00:46:38,835
Seoul, Santa Monica, and other regions.

650
00:46:38,835 --> 00:46:42,137
So if you're interested, hit me up on Twitter.

